# Approach
This approach uses a dynamic programming method to solve the problem of finding the nth number in the tribonacci sequence. The basic idea is to use a cache (in this case, an ArrayList) to store the already computed values of the sequence, so that they can be reused in future calculations.

The main function, tribonacci(int n), starts by checking if the value of n is already stored in the cache. If it is, it simply returns the value from the cache. If not, the function calculates the value by adding up the three previous values in the sequence (tribonacci(n-3) + tribonacci(n-2) + tribonacci(n-1)), and then stores the result in the cache for future use.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n), because each value of n is calculated only once and stored in the cache, so subsequent calculations are done in constant time.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n), because the cache stores the values of n.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# JAVA
```
class Solution {
    static ArrayList<Integer> cache = new ArrayList<Integer>(Arrays.asList(0, 1, 1));

    public static int tribonacci(int n) {
        // check if the value of n is already in the cache
        if (n >= cache.size() || cache.get(n) == null) {
            // if not, add the value to the cache by calculating the tribonacci sequence
            cache.add(tribonacci(n - 3) + tribonacci(n - 2) + tribonacci(n - 1));
        }
        // return the value from the cache
        return cache.get(n);
    }
}

```
