solutions.content:
#### **Intuition:**
* There is not much about the problem, as we have define a sequence (called as  N-th Tribonacci) and have to give result on the basis of that sequence.
* The sequence is defind as Tn+3 = Tn + Tn+1 + Tn+2.
* Also some base cases are also included here as (T0 = 0, T1 = 1, T2 = 1 ).
* We will implement this only.
____________
##### **Recursive (TLE):**
* Recursive solution hits first, as that is what same as asked in the question.
* With gives bases cases we will apply that relation in our program.

**CODES:**
* **C++ / JAVA (BOTH ARE SAME):**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int tribonacci(int n) {
        if(n == 0)
            return 0;
        if(n == 1 || n == 2)
            return 1;

        return tribonacci(n - 1) +  tribonacci(n - 2) +  tribonacci(n - 3);
   }
};
```
__________
##### **DP (MEMOZIATION):**
* We will receive **TLE with recursive code**, and question arises **why** ?
* See, One cool thing about our recursive codes is that, when they call themself and for some smaller input cases,
they treat that input case as new problem, even they already computed that problem before.
* What I meant to say, suppose for n = 4 we call our recursive function 
then, recursive function goes something like as T4 = T3 + T2 + T1.
* Now, for again T3 it goes like T3 = T2 + T1 + T0.
* Now, bases cases hit and we will get our answer.
* But suppose someone asks us about n = 5, then it compute for n = 5 as T5 = T4 + T3 + T2.
* Now, T4, T3, T2, ***all three will be treated as brand new problem***, but we just computed our value for T4 above,
but recursive function says no it dosen’t matter for me, I will again compute them again and then again give result.
* So, this is the problem in our recursive solution as for some already computed result,
we are not taking advantage of that we simply compute again when we encounter some result.
* So, Now question arises how can we get rid of this problem i.e computing again and again.
* We will say why we are computing again a problem, because are not memorizing it, or precisely say we are not remembering it.
* So we make a table and stores all that result which are already computed,
and then if in some later process we need that values we will pick them from our table.

* Annnnnd, this is what exactly dp is!!!

```
TIME AND SPACE COMPLEXITY:
Time Complexity: O(n) 
Space Complexity: O(n) // because we are using dp table here
```
**CODES:**
* C++:
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long dp[38] = {0};
    int tribonacci(int n) {

        if(n == 0)
            return 0;
        if(n == 1 || n == 2)
            return 1;

        if(dp[n] != 0)
            return dp[n];

       return dp[n] =  tribonacci(n - 1) +  tribonacci(n - 2) +  tribonacci(n - 3);

    }
};
```
* JAVA:
```
class Solution {
    int [] dp = new int[38];
    public int solve(int n)
    {
        if(n == 0)
            return 0;
        if(n == 1 || n == 2)
            return 1;

        if(dp[n] != 0)
            return dp[n];

        return dp[n] = solve(n - 1) +  solve(n - 2) +  solve(n - 3);
    }
    public int tribonacci(int n) {
        Arrays.fill(dp, 0);
        return solve(n);
    }
}
```
____________
##### **DP (BOTTOM UP APPROACH):**
* Instead of recursive code, we can use iterative method also, but the idea will be same.
* And also, there is no change in Time and Space Complexity here.
* They remain same as O(n).

**CODES**
* **C++ / JAVA (BOTH ARE SAME):**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int tribonacci(int n) {
        if(n == 0) return 0;
        if(n == 1 || n == 2) return 1;

        int dp[n + 1];
        dp[0] = 0, dp[1] = dp[2] = 1;

        for(int i = 3; i <= n; i++)
        {
            dp[i] = dp[i - 1] + dp[i - 2] + dp[i - 3];
        }

        return dp[n];
    }
};
```
_______________
#### **Now, Question arises do we really need a table here:**
* Answer is **NO**.
* If we observe our problem here at a particular instant of time in calculating any ‘n’, we **only required the value of last three variables here**.
* SO, why to make a table in calculating any answer.
* We will make three variables to store the previous last three values and then calculate our answer.
* It decreases our space complexity from O(n) to O(1).

```
TIME AND SPACE COMPLEXITY:
Time Complexity: O(n) 
Space Complexity: O(1)
```

**CODES:**
* **C++ / JAVA (BOTH ARE SAME):**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int tribonacci(int n) {
        if(n == 0) return 0;
        if(n == 1 || n == 2) return 1;

        int LastThird = 0, LastSecond = 1, JustLast = 1;

        while(n > 2)
        {
            int sum = LastThird + LastSecond + JustLast;

            LastThird = LastSecond;
            LastSecond = JustLast;
            JustLast = sum;
            n--;
        }

        return JustLast;
    }
};
```
