# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
For this problem, we need to understand how **Fibonacci Series** work. In **Fibonacci series**, the present element is sum of previous three elements. 

In **Tribonacci Series**, the present element is sum of previous THREE elements, hence the name.
```cpp
Trib_4 = Trib_1 + Trib_2 + Trib_3
Trib_5 = Trib_2 + Trib_3 + Trib_4

```
I think you can see how the dynamic programming approach will work by looking at these two equations.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
There can be two approaches to this problem, One is the naive recursive method and other involves Dynamic Programming approach.

I won't discuss the recursive approach because it is very inefficient.
```
T(n) = T(n-1) + T(n-2) + T(n-3)

```
Here, *T(n) = O($3^{n}$)*

In the DP approach, we are starting off with the first 3 base cases, and for inputs larger than these, the for loop gets executed.

We store the sum of previous three elements in the ans variable and then update the auxillary variables.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: **O(n)**
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Since we are iterating only once


- Space complexity: **O(1)**
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Contant time since no matter what is the input size, the auxillary variables are of fixed size.
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int tribonacci(int n) { 
        // This program is based on zeroth indexing
        if(n < 3 && n > 0){ // Base case for n = 1, 2
            return 1;
        }
        if (n==0){ // Base case for n = 0
            return n;
        }
        int t0 = 0, t1 = 1, t2 = 1; // Initializing the auxillary variables
        int ans = 0; // Answer variable
        for(int i = 2 ; i < n ; i++){
            ans = t0 + t1 + t2; // Adding the previous three numbers
            // Updating the variables for next iteration
            t0 = t1;
            t1 = t2;
            t2 = ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

