solutions.content:
Like fibonacci, a classic recursion with memoization problem, we can apply the same approach to tribonacci.

Given:  Tn+3 = Tn+0 + Tn+1 + Tn+2,
we know: Tn = Tn-3 + Tn-2 + Tn-1.
So the plain/brute-force recursion solution would be:
```
if(n == 0) return 0;
if(n == 1) return 1;
if(n == 2) return 1;
return tribonacci(n-3) + tribonacci(n-2) + tribonacci(n-1);
```

However this wastes a lot of time recalculating the same values over and over. We should store these, "memoize", and access as needed instead of recalculating.
Since N is guaranteed to be constrained within 0 - 37, we can store this in an array.

Time complexity: O(n). Only calculate every value of n once, otherwise we return in O(1).
Space complexity: O(1). Store a constant 38 integer array.


```
class Solution {
    int[] memo;

    Solution() {
        // Initialize memo, with -1 as flags for not calculated
        memo = new int[38]; // 0 through 37
        memo[0] = 0;
        memo[1] = 1;
        memo[2] = 1;
        for(int i = 3; i < memo.length; i++) memo[i] = -1;
    }

    public int tribonacci(int n) {
        // If we have already calculated value, return it.
        if(memo[n] != -1) {
            return memo[n];
        }
        else {
            int result = tribonacci(n-3) + tribonacci(n-2) + tribonacci(n-1);
            memo[n] = result;
            return result;
        }
    }
}
```

