solutions.content:
- We might have two types of points: 
	1. Points that are at the location; 2. Points that are not at the location
- For case 1, we can simply use a constant count, to count how many points are at the location
- For case 2, we calculate the angle between the location and the point; then push them to array
- To calculate the angle: first find the radius, then convert to degree 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/507ca860-115d-4616-889b-7b9a5ea1c0ed_1651172880.6333077.jpeg)

- If degree is negative, push degree+360 to the array; then sort the array
- Use Sliding window to find the max visible points (not at location)
- Return the max visible points (not at location) and count (all points that are at the location)

Video explanation: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9fAkEkKSDwM&t=791s
```
var visiblePoints = function(points, angle, location) {
    let [dx, dy] = location, count = 0, arr = [];
    for ([x,y] of points) {
        if (x == dx && y == dy) count++;
        else arr.push(Math.atan2(y-dy, x-dx) * 180 / Math.PI);
    }
    for (a of arr) if (a<0) arr.push(a+360);
    arr.sort((a,b) => a-b);
    let l = r = res = 0;
    while (r < arr.length) {
        while (arr[r] - arr[l] > angle) l++;
        res = Math.max(res, r-l+1);
        r++; 
    }
    return res + count; 
};
```

