solutions.content:
The idea is to convert all points into an array of angles to the original location, and perform sliding window on the circular array to find the one maximum points.

The tricky part is to handle the sliding window on the circular array, I see some post doing this by adding another set of 360 degree and make it from 0-720. my way of doing this is little bit complicated by judging if the second point is out of the array and add 360 to it.  

```
class Solution {
    public int visiblePoints(List<List<Integer>> points, int angle, List<Integer> location) {
        List<Double> angles = new ArrayList<Double>();
        int count = 0;

        for(List<Integer> point:points){
            double y = (double)(point.get(1)-location.get(1));
            double x = (double)(point.get(0)-location.get(0));
            if(x==0&&y==0){
                count++;
                continue;
            }
            double thisAngle = 180*Math.atan(y/x)/Math.PI;
            if(x<0) thisAngle = 180.0 + thisAngle;
            else if(y<0) thisAngle = 360.0 + thisAngle;
            angles.add(thisAngle);  
        }


        Collections.sort(angles);
        //System.out.println(Arrays.toString(angles.toArray()));

        int max=0, start=0,end=0, n=angles.size();
        double window=0.0;

        // circular sliding window
        while(start<n){
            //end = start;
            while((end>=n?angles.get(end%n)+360:angles.get(end))-angles.get(start)<=angle){
                end++;
            }
            if(end>start){
                max = Math.max(end-start,max);
            }else{
                max = Math.max(end+n-start-1,max);
            }

            start++;
        }

        return max+count;
    }
}
