solutions.content:
I keep seeing people post JS solutions where they rely on the map implementation to keep their integer keys sorted for them and claim that makes it O(N). 

I'm going to go on record as being pretty damn skeptical about those claims - presumably the underlying interface must either maintain an integer sort order or generate one on the fly. Regardless of my distate, I experienced a bout of temporary insanity and wound up actually writing one of those "O(N)" implementations for this problem.

At one point there was actually a sensible idea in here: you could potentially improve the base algorithm by maintaining a count of identical points. It's probably not a practical improvement considering the increased code complexity and how unlikely it is to actually happen in the real world. But hey, if you want to repurpose it in some *actually sensible* code then go ahead.

##### "Does it work?" 
Who cares, it passes all tests! You could argue that this means the test cases are insufficient but honestly I think they're fine. It's not strictly 100% accurate but the edge cases are incredibly tiny.
##### Is it faster than other approaches? 
Hahaha hell no!
##### Could it be improved further? 
Almost certainly! You might even trim it down to being a viable algorithm! But please don't!
##### Should you improve it yourself? 
Please do not! I suffered to prevent others from writing code this **incredibly stupid**.

[I also posted a real solution if you're more interested in that kind of thing.](https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-number-of-visible-points/discuss/1924110/Efficient-sliding-window-solution-with-comments)

```
/**
 * @param {number[][]} points
 * @param {number} angle
 * @param {number[]} location
 * @return {number}
 */
const getDegrees = (p1, p2) => (Math.atan2(p1[1] - p2[1], p1[0] - p2[0]) * 180 / Math.PI) + 180;

// Maximum amount we can multiply a float by before it is no longer treated as an int
const SCALING_FACTOR = 10000000;

var visiblePoints = function(points, angle, location) {
    angle = angle * SCALING_FACTOR;
    // Early offramp if there aren't enough points for this to be a complex problem
    if(points.length < 2) return points.length;

    // Separate the points into the ones which we're already standing on
    // vs the ones that we need to actually look at, and convert both into
    // more directly usable values
    let angles = {};
    let onCenter = 0;
    for(let p of points) {
        if(p[0] === location[0] && p[1] === location[1]) {
            onCenter++;
        } else {
            const deg = Math.round(getDegrees(p, location) * SCALING_FACTOR);
            angles[deg] = (angles[deg] || 0) + 1; 
        }
    }

    let keys = Object.keys(angles); 
    const N = keys.length;
    // No need to do any more work if we're standing on every available angle
    if(!N) return onCenter;

    const diff = SCALING_FACTOR * 360;
    const highest = keys[N-1] + angle;
    for(let key of keys) {
        const newKey = new Number(key) + diff;
        if(newKey > highest) break;
        angles[newKey] = angles[key];
    }
    keys = Object.keys(angles);

    // It is actually possible that there's no remaining angles to check here
    let best = 0;
    // Maintain a sliding window of valid points
    let right = 1;

    let current = 0;
    let stretched = false;

    for(let left = 0; left < N; left++) {
        const start = keys[left];

        // Ensure that we're not about to use an invalid window
        if(keys[right] <= start) {
            current = 0;
            right = left + 1;
            stretched = false;
        }
        current += angles[start];

        // Attempt to continue the existing window (or the freshly constructed one!)
        while(right < keys.length) {
            if(new Number(start) + angle >= keys[right]) {
                current += angles[keys[right++]];
                stretched = true;
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }

        best = Math.max(best, current);
        current -= angles[start];
        if (stretched) {
            current -= angles[keys[left+1]];
            if(left+1 === right) {
                stretched = false;
            }
        }
    }

    return best + onCenter;
};
```

