solutions.content:
With `m` and `n` constrained to `8`, it's feasible to just check all permutations.

We just check all possible assignments for each student `i`, using `mask` to track mentors that have been assigned. We track and return the maximum score.

To speed things up, we can use memoisation, where we store interim results for each `i` and `mask`.

**C++**
```cpp
int dp[256] = {[0 ... 255] = -1};
int maxCompatibilitySum(vector<vector<int>>& s, vector<vector<int>>& m, int i = 0, int mask = 0) {
    if (i == s.size())
        return 0;
    if (dp[mask] < 0)
        for (int j = 0; j < m.size(); ++j) {
            if ((mask & (1 << j)) == 0)
                dp[mask] = max(dp[mask], 
                    inner_product(begin(s[i]), end(s[i]), begin(m[j]), 0, plus<int>(), equal_to<int>())
                    + maxCompatibilitySum(s, m, i + 1, mask + (1 << j)));
        }
    return dp[mask];
}
```

